Lab 03: Dealing with Merge Conflicts

Fall 2019

Step 1: Everyone: Clone your assignment repo in RStudio Cloud (merge-conflicts-TEAMNAME), and open the R Markdown file. Don’t forget to configure git!

library(usethis)
use_git_config(user.name="GITHUB USERNAME", user.email="your email")


Step 2: Assign the numbers 1, 2, 3, and 4 to each of the team members. Member 4 should look at the group’s repo on GitHub.com to ensure that the other members’ files are pushed to GitHub after every step.

Step 3: Take turns in completing the steps below exactly as written, only one member at a time:

  • Member 1: Change the team name to your team name. Knit, commit, and push.

  • Member 2: Change the team name something different, i.e. not your team name. Knit, commit, push. You will get an error.

    • Pull and review the document with the merge conflict. Show the error to your teammates.
    • A merge conflict occurred because you edited the same part of the document as Member 1. Resolve the conflict with whichever name you want to keep.
    • Knit, commit and push.

  • Member 3: Use the diamonds dataset to create a plot displaying the relationship between price and carat, controlling for cut of the diamonds dataset (see below for the plot). Note: You can control fro the cut by using the “color” option in the aes().

    • Knit, commit, push. You will get an error, read it, and pull. Show the error to your teammates.
    • No merge conflicts should occur, since you edited a different part of the document from Members 1 and 2.
    • Knit, commit, and push.

Step 4: All members: Pull, and observe the changes in your document.

Plot for Member 3 to create
